%N A387935 Numbers k such that Sum_{i=1..r} (k-i) and Sum_{i=1..s} (k+i) are both prime (A000040) for some 1 <= r < k, 1 <= s < k.
%C A387935 Union of A088763 and A014574.
%C A387935 The least r, s = 1 or 2, thus we have: k = (p_1 + p_2)/2 or k = (p_1 + p_2 - 2)/3 or k = (p_1 + p_2 + 2)/3 or k = (p_1 + p_2)/4 where p_1 != p_2 are prime numbers.
%H A387935 Robert Israel, <a href="/A387935/b387935.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A387935 For k = 5: the least r = 2, 3 + 4 = 7 is a prime, 6 + 7 = 13 is a prime, thus k = 5 is a term.
%p A387935 filter:= t -> (isprime(t+1) and isprime(t-1)) or (isprime(2*t+3) and isprime(2*t-3)):
%p A387935 select(filter, [$1..300]); # _Robert Israel_, Sep 21 2025
